<p>We can use desktops to differentiate our workspaces, such as using Deskt=
op 1 for development IDEs and terminals, Desktop 2 for browsers and documen=
t writing, Desktop 3 for handling communication tools like WeChat and email=
, and Desktop 4 for leisure and video playback. This way, we only need to s=
witch between a few desktops to implement our workflow logic without worryi=
ng about window focus issues.</p>
<p>To further optimize and quickly switch between desktops, we can use laun=
chers like <a href=3D"https://www.alfredapp.com/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"=
noopener noreferrer">Alfred</a> or <a href=3D"https://www.raycast.com/" tar=
get=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Raycast</a> to quickly launch/fo=
cus applications, and we can also use window switching software like <a hre=
f=3D"https://alt-tab-macos.netlify.app/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener =
noreferrer">AltTab</a> or <a href=3D"https://manico.im/" target=3D"_blank" =
rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Manico</a> to provide shortcuts for quickly swi=
tching between opened applications.</p>
<p>Additionally, the macOS system settings also provide custom shortcut opt=
ions for switching. I modified <code>&lt;Option&gt; + &lt;1~9&gt;</code> to=
 correspond to specific desktops, so when working, I can quickly switch to =
the corresponding workspace by pressing the corresponding shortcut key, whi=
ch quickly forms muscle memory.</p>
<p>Open <strong>System Preferences - Keyboard - Shortcuts - Mission Control=
</strong>, and we can set corresponding shortcuts for different desktops. I=
f they do not appear, you can first open 9 empty desktops for configuration=
, and the settings will remain even after closing the desktops.</p>
